Lindsay Clark Roberts was a true friend. But what does that mean, exactly? It means that you could be you in her presence, and she could be her, and it felt like home. 

When she was first diagnosed with brain cancer at 23/24, I remember my mom called her and told her to believe the diagnosis but never the prognosis. That stuck with her and it stuck with me. She beat it. 

But when she messaged me on October 7, 2021 (after we had weeks prior discovered her brain cancer had returned) and said, “I’m going to die from brain cancer,” we both knew that prognosis was true. It was a horrifying thought and in all honesty I didn’t know what to say. We talked about logistics and she said she would accept chemo (even though she didn’t want to—who would if the cancer is going to kill you anyway?) because she wanted to make sure her young son knew his mom did everything she could to be with him as long as possible. 

That’s who Lindsay was. 

I saw a post that Christie McConnell, Lindsay’s big sister, made on our sorority FB group in which she said Lindsay “was funny and thoughtful and sometimes terrifying.”

I couldn’t agree more. Lindsay could be terrifying in the best way, as she would never accept shit from anyone and she fought for herself, her family, and her friends until the very end. 

I love you, Linds. I never told you, but the name Lindsay was one of the names on my list when I discovered I was pregnant with a girl. I wanted my child to be a fierce, independent, trailblazer. And while we decided on Maya (since the great Maya Angelou is also all of those things), it could have just as easily been for you.

A week ago today on February 1st, my mom Margaret passed away. 

I had been preparing for this news, especially in the last month, but it still came as a sudden shock. 

As you may know, Mom had not been well for quite a while. Mentally and emotionally I have been grieving her for a long time, and grieving someone while they are still alive is difficult (to say the least.) Grieving a person who has passed is difficult, but for me it also comes with some release. I am so, so glad she is no longer suffering and is at peace. 

I am usually good with words but I’m not sure what to say that would fully encompass all the feelings and emotions that we’ve been going through for the last week, let alone the last months and years. 

What I’d really like to do here instead is ask a favor. If you have fond memories of my mom, please share them. I would love to look back and discover or remember good times, before we knew what a meningioma brain tumor was, and start my healing process. 

I love you, mom. I am grateful for the love you freely gave, the strength you displayed, the fortitude you possessed, the humor you shared, the courage you mustered, the kindness you offered. Thank you for everything.

Edit to say: I’m fine and we are LOVING our home at @hits961 🥰 But when a former station flips, it’s emotional!! 

The end of an era. When you pour your heart and soul, your blood, sweat, and tears into a radio station, it becomes a living breathing entity that’s part of you and your journey. I’m thankful for what we gained at our time at Hot 101.5, for the amazing fam we were able to connect and bond with, for the community we created. The sound will probably get muted on this reel, but Party Rock Anthem will always be our anthem. I’m truly proud of what @miguelfuller and I accomplished during our time at Hot, along with our producers, @niccinunez, @onairwithjd, @tampabayphotographer, and @scotttavlin, who shaped us for the better. To our PDs, @djwillcalder, @cscdanmason, @johnekage, @fmradiorico, and @timclarke, thank you for the lessons and support. Cheers to us today. And cheers to you, all of you, who found a home with us.
